-- Syllogism (Function Composition)
--
-- Classical: A -> B, B -> C |- A -> C
-- CredTT: f : A -> B @ c1, g : B -> C @ c2 |- g . f : A -> C @ c1 * c2
--
-- Example: All men are mortal; Socrates is a man; Socrates is mortal
-- Classical: Definite conclusion
-- CredTT: Credences multiply through composition

-- Classical syllogism:
-- Major: All M are P
-- Minor: All S are M
-- Conclusion: All S are P

-- In CredTT, each step has a credence:
postulate major : all_M_are_P @ c1
postulate minor : all_S_are_M @ c2

-- Composition: credences multiply
-- If c1 = 0.95 and c2 = 0.90, then c1 * c2 = 0.855

-- This captures the real-world phenomenon:
-- Chains of reasoning DEGRADE confidence

-- Each step in a long proof multiplies credences:
-- Step 1: c1
-- Step 2: c1 * c2
-- Step 3: c1 * c2 * c3
-- ...
-- Step n: c1 * c2 * ... * cn

-- Even if each step is 0.99, after 100 steps:
-- 0.99^100 = 0.366 (much less than 1!)

-- This is WHY long proofs can be less reliable
-- Classical logic hides this; CredTT exposes it

-- Stable composition:
postulate f_stable : f_A_to_B @ 1
postulate g_stable : g_B_to_C @ 1

-- 1 * 1 = 1, stability preserved
derive composed : g_compose_f @ 1 from f_stable by compose

stable f_stable
stable g_stable
stable composed

-- Weak link in chain:
postulate f_weak : f_weak_A_to_B @ 1/2
postulate g_ok : g_ok_B_to_C @ 1

-- 1 * 0.5 = 0.5, credence degrades to weakest link
-- (Actually: product, which is even worse if both weak)

-- The syllogism is only as strong as its weakest premise
-- times all the other premises!
